We also have Braille for music.
We use Braille letters from d to j.
For example, the letter "d" is for the "do" sound.
We have Braille in Japanese, too.
You can find Braille on elevator buttons, vending machines and many other things.
Look for Braille around you.
Blind people use Braille for reading and writing.
They use their fingers and read Braille.
One Braille letter has one to six dots.
Braille has the capital sign for capital letters and the number sign for numbers.
We have Braille for music and Japanese, too.
We can often see Braille on many things around us.
